## Async Functions (asynchronous functions)
Basic Syntax
async function functionName() {
  // asynchronous code
}

or arrow function:

const functionName = async () => {
  // async code
};

Key Points

async → makes a function return a Promise 
  ## A Promise is exactly what it sounds like: a placeholder for a value that you don't have yet but will receive in the future.
await → pauses execution until Promise resolves

   ## The await Keyword (The Magic)
   #  The await keyword can only be used inside an async function. It tells JavaScript: "Pause the  execution of this specific function until the promise is resolved."

  #  Crucially, it doesn't freeze the whole browser; it just pauses the code inside that one     function.

Makes async code look like normal step-by-step code

## When you put the word async before a function, you are turning it into an Asynchronous Function.

async function myFunc() {
  return "Hello!";
}
    // Even though we returned a string, 
    // JavaScript automatically wraps it in a Promise.
console.log(myFunc()); 
        // Output: Promise { 'Hello!' }

Simple async function

async function greet() {
  return "Hello";
}
greet().then((msg) => console.log(msg));



example2: 
function waitTwoSeconds() {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {           //await only works on a Promise so we use promise
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve("Done after 2 seconds");       
    }, 2000);
  });
}      //A Promise needs to know when it is "finished. so we used resolve to tell the Promise that  it's done and what value it should return.

async function run() {
  let result = await waitTwoSeconds();
  console.log(result);
}
run();

## Create a New Promise that makes the code Await (pause) here. Start a Timer for 2000ms. Once that timer rings, call the Resolve function to tell the Promise we are finished so the code can continue.

👉 Flow:
run() starts
await pauses
2 seconds later Promise resolves
prints result

👉 An async function is a function that returns a Promise and allows writing asynchronous code using await in a synchronous style.

## better way to understand 

Sync vs Async: The "Phone Call" Analogy
Think about how you communicate with a friend:

## Synchronous (The Phone Call):
You call your friend to ask for a quote. They say, "Hold on, let me find my book." You stay on the phone, listening to silence, holding the phone to your ear. You cannot do anything else because your hand and ear are busy. You are "blocked."

## Asynchronous (The Text Message):
You text your friend: "Send me a quote." You put your phone in your pocket. You go wash the dishes, watch TV, and talk to your family. Ten minutes later, your phone pings. You check the message and see the quote. You weren't stuck waiting; you were "non-blocked."

## Where you use it
You will almost always use async in these 3 situations:
      Network Requests: Getting data from an API (like your project).

      Databases: Saving or reading user info.

      Files: Opening a very large image or document.